Secured and Monitored Web Infrastructure
Infrastructure Design

When a user types www.foobar.com
, the DNS resolves it to the IP of the load balancer. The request is sent over HTTPS using an SSL certificate to ensure encryption.

The load balancer (HAproxy) distributes traffic between two servers (Active-Active). Each server contains a web server (Nginx), an application server, and the application code.

The application communicates with a MySQL database cluster (Primary-Replica). The primary handles writes, while the replica handles reads.

Each server is protected by a firewall, and each one has a monitoring client that sends data to a monitoring service.

Why we added these components
Firewalls: to protect servers from unauthorized access
SSL certificate (HTTPS): to encrypt data between the user and the server
Monitoring clients: to track performance, errors, and system health
Explanations

What are firewalls for?
Firewalls filter incoming and outgoing traffic and block malicious requests.

Why HTTPS?
HTTPS encrypts data, protecting sensitive information from attackers.

What is monitoring used for?
Monitoring helps detect issues, track performance, and ensure the system is running properly.

How does monitoring collect data?
Monitoring agents (clients) run on each server and send logs and metrics to a central monitoring system.

How to monitor web server QPS?
By configuring the monitoring tool to track the number of requests handled by the web server per second using logs or metrics.

Issues in this Infrastructure
SSL termination at load balancer: traffic between load balancer and servers may not be encrypted
Single MySQL write node: if the primary fails, write operations stop
Same components on all servers: reduces efficiency and makes scaling harder
